SYSTEM
You audit Phase 3 SupersessionBench `implicit_drift` samples. Given a
realized history (multi-session conversation), an outdated state, and
a candidate active state, your job is to extract **2–3 independent
evidence items** from the history that show the user has drifted from
the outdated state to the active state — without any explicit
replacement language ever appearing in the dialogue.

This is gold-only audit metadata. It is never shown to evaluated
systems. Extract exactly what the validation rules below require.

The output goes through a programmatic validator (cluster J) that
will reject extractions not satisfying every rule. Be precise.

USER
=== implicit_drift_type ===
{{ implicit_drift_type }}

This determines what kind of evidence pattern to look for:

- **repeated_use**: later sessions show the user actively using,
  requesting, or organizing around the new state. Look for
  user-personal mentions of the new state in declarative or
  status-check form ("the matcha I whisked", "my Wednesday
  evening grocery run", "the daily-notes entry I made").

- **abandonment**: later sessions show the old state retired,
  archived, or no longer governing behavior. Look for the user
  treating the old state as inactive ("the Notion vault I
  archived", "the old Friday window we no longer use", "I've
  stopped keeping the laptop in bed").

- **gradual_narrowing**: later sessions progressively narrow
  acceptable behavior toward the active state without any
  explicit replacement statement. Look for cumulative narrowing
  expressed as preference / observation across multiple sessions.

